><ForeName>Wolfram</ForeName><Initials>W</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0000-8537-0577</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Autolus Therapeutics Weil am Rhein, Baden Wurttemberg Germany.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lao-Sirieix</LastName><ForeName>Pierre</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0003-4363-0520</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Autolus Therapeutics Weil am Rhein, Baden Wurttemberg Germany.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bishop</LastName><ForeName>Michael R</ForeName><Initials>MR</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-3979-9273</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Chicago Chicago, ILL United States.</Affiliation><Identifier Source="ROR">https://ror.org/024mw5h28</Identifier></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>DeAngelo</LastName><ForeName>Daniel J</ForeName><Initials>DJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-7865-2306</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Dana-Farber Cancer Institute Boston, MA United States.</Affiliation><Identifier Source="ROR">https://ror.org/02jzgtq86</Identifier></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jabbour</LastName><ForeName>Elias</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-4465-6119</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center Houston, TX United States.</Affiliation><Identifier Source="ROR">https://ror.org/04twxam07</Identifier></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Park</LastName><ForeName>Jae H</ForeName><Initials>JH</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-2903-5130</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center New York, NY United States.</Affiliation><Identifier Source="ROR">https://ror.org/02yrq0923</Identifier></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>04</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Cancer Res Commun</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>9918281580506676</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2767-9764</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>3</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>17</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="revised"><Year>2026</Year><Month>4</Month><Day>22</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>4</Day><Hour>18</Hour><Minute>42</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>4</Day><Hour>18</Hour><Minute>42</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>4</Day><Hour>16</Hour><Minute>43</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42241689</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1158/2767-9764.CRC-25-0756</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">785704</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">41504229</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>08</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1592-8721</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>111</Volume><Issue>6</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Haematologica</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Haematologica</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Tumor burden-guided dosing contributes to mitigation of immunotoxicities following treatment with obecabtagene autoleucel in adult patients with relapsed/refractory B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1999</StartPage><EndPage>2010</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1999-2010</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3324/haematol.2025.288587</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Obecabtagene autoleucel (obe-cel) is a CD19-targeted autologous chimeric antigen receptor T-cell therapy (CAR T) with a fast off-rate binding domain, administered as split-dose infusions guided by pre-lymphodepletion tumor burden (low-tumor- burden [TB] group: &#x2264;20%; high-TB group: &gt;20% bone marrow [BM] blasts). Obe-cel treatment in adult relapsed/refractory B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (R/R B-ALL) was investigated in the phase Ib/II FELIX trial. Here, we report pharmacokinetics, safety, and efficacy outcomes in patients with low or high tumor burden and discuss the evidence/rationale justifying the spilt-dose strategy and threshold used to classify the groups. Tumor burden at lymphodepletion was a critical driver of CAR T-cell expansion; a 50% increase, e.g., 70% versus 20% BM blasts, was associated with a 1.9-fold increase (95% confidence interval: 1.4-2.6) in maximal expansion of CAR T cells. Robust CAR T-cell expansion was observed in both tumor burden groups. The incidence of grade &#x2265;3 cytokine release syndrome and immune effector cell-associated neurotoxicity syndrome was minimal in both the low- and high-TB groups (2% vs. 3% and 4% vs. 9%, respectively). Although the overall remission rate was higher in the low-TB group (85%), it also remained high in the high-TB group (73%). Evidence from FELIX suggests that use of tumor burden--guided dosing may mitigate the typical effects of immunotoxicity while maintaining substantial efficacy. Although further study is needed to better characterize the effects of the split-dosing strategy, the clinical evidence supports its use when administering obe-cel for the treatment of R/R B-ALL. Trial registered at www.clinicaltrial. gov (clinicaltrials gov. Identifier: NCT04404660).</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jabbour</LastName><ForeName>Elias</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center, Houston, TX. ejabbour@mdanderson.org.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sandhu</LastName><ForeName>Karamjeet S</ForeName><Initials>KS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>City of Hope National Medical Center, Duarte, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Shaughnessy</LastName><ForeName>Paul</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Sarah Cannon Transplant and Cellular Therapy Program, Methodist Hospital, San Antonio, TX.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Logan</LastName><ForeName>Aaron C</ForeName><Initials>AC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Hematology, Blood and Marrow Transplantation, and Cellular Therapy Program, University of California at San Francisco, San Francisco, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Abedi</LastName><ForeName>Mehrdad</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of California Davis, Davis, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Shah</LastName><ForeName>Bijal D</ForeName><Initials>BD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Moffitt Cancer Center, Tampa, FL.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bishop</LastName><ForeName>Michael R</ForeName><Initials>MR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The David and Etta Jonas Center for Cellular Therapy, University of Chicago, Chicago, IL.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author 